description:
The eggs are done!

The aim of Ovo is to get all of your eggs back home after they've been flipped over in your opponent's camp. On the way to that camp, the players' symbols on each egg are visible &ndash; 
but on the way back those symbols are hidden so that the eggs, which can be moved by any player, are no longer identifiable. Since nothing looks more like an egg than another egg, your challenge is to keep track of your eggs as they hop, skip and jump their way home!

From the game's booklet:

&laquo;Bello and his friends have absconded during the dog show. Who will be the first to find Bello and his brother in the frolicking crowd? But it's not that simple, because Henry is the spitting image of the two dogs. Who collects the most dogs?&raquo;

Bello is a matching pairs game for children, with a twist. As the game goes by and players get more pairs, it's harder to claim new dogs by their right names.

OrgasMe! is sex turned into a card game. 2-6 players take turns at drawing cards and attacking each other with funny or sometimes crazy sex attacks.
&nbsp;
Each player gets an OrgasMeter, which is a cardboard device that displays the level of a person&rsquo;s horniness in units of 1 Horn. Exceeding the measuring range of 10 Horn means that you&rsquo;re having an orgasm.
&nbsp;
Being attacked with an action card increases your horniness by 1 Horn. All other types of cards are either of defensive or offensive use to avoid the end of the game: The first player having an orgasm loses the game.
&nbsp;
To win the game you must not cum first! The clever use of your cards and special abilities might turn the tide of the game if you play them just at the right moment.

from RULES TRANSLATION:

You travel up and down the Loire with your wheel steamer. By transporting passengers and wine barrels, you fill your cash register with Louis d'Or, the currency of the time. The more stokers you hire, the further your ship travels. The more boatswains you have, the better you can assert yourself against your rivals if you head for a mooring at the shore.

The goal of the game is, by transporting passengers and wine barrels, to acquire the most Louis d'Or.

Description from products website:

&ldquo;Set sail for the New World across uncharted waters,where unseen Sea Monsters are lurking below the waves. Navigate through typhoons, get blown off course and even drift out to sea. And just when you think your home free,a Sea Monster may appear out of nowhere to wreck your ship!&rdquo;

Contents: 8 Sea Monsters/Wave Cards,12 Ships (4 colors),4 port of call cards,8 storm at sea cards, Seafarer's Die (Blue), Sea Monster's Die (Green),rules.

Each card is illustrated with shapes and numbers.  The game play is simple - just match the shape or number on your card with the shape or number on the previous card.  The first player to get rid of all their cards is the winner! Like Uno without the special cards!

There are five suits: stars, circles, squares, crosses and triangles. You can change suit by laying the same number as has been laid in the suit you lay down yourself. Also, the card numbered 20 (WHOT Card) can be used to change from a suit to any other suit at any time.  When the first person has finished, the others count up how many penalty points they have on the cards they have left in their hand. (Star cards count double as indicated by the second smaller figure in the small star). More recent decks also give the suits different colours, stars are blue, circles yellow, crosses red, triangles green, and squares purple.

&lsquo;Whot! was invented (but, apparently, not patented) and trademarked by William Henry Storey, of Southend-on-Sea, England in 1935. It was first marketed by the company Storey & Co of Croydon, which he set up in 1930, but was soon acquired by Waddingtons of Leeds, and was popular in Britain in the 1950s and 1960s.&rsquo;

&ldquo; &hellip; Let me say that our system of government does not copy the institutions of our neighbors. It is more the case of our being a model to others than of our imitating anyone else. Our constitution is called a democracy because power is in the hands not of a minority but of the whole people&hellip;

&hellip; When our work is over, we are in a position to enjoy all kinds of recreation for our spirits. There are various kinds of contests and sacrifices regularly throughout the year; in our own homes we find a beauty and a good taste which delight us every day and which drive away our cares. Then the greatness of our city brings it about that all the good things from all over the world flow in to us, so that to us it seems just as natural to enjoy foreign goods as our own local products&hellip;

&hellip; Future ages will wonder at us, as the present age wonders at us now&hellip;&rdquo; 
&ndash;  Pericles

In the 5th century B.C., through the Persian wars, the Delian league was founded under the leadership of Athens&mdash;this alliance was actually the Athenian empire. Athens became the wealthiest and strongest city-state in the world, but she also faced difficult challenges from inside and outside of her. In Athens, players acting in the role of leaders in the heyday of Athens would contribute to its sustainable prosperity.

Athens is played over a maximum of 14 rounds. There are four phases to complete each round: People Management Phase, Base Phase, Action Phase, and Event Phase. You will expand your base, manage the people and then perform an event in every round: preparing for war by raising armies, holding a festival with trading goods, and so on. You need not only to make an effective plan but also accept a bit of uncertainty. By the grace of goddess Athena, your leadership will make Athens greater!

&mdash;description from the publisher
